- $\Phi_2'$ is $(-1/(z-1))^2$
- $\Phi_3'$ is $(-1/z)^2$
- $\Phi_4'$ is $(-1/(z+1))^2$ (same as $\Phi_1'$)
- $\Phi_5'$ is $(-1/z)^2$ (same as $\Phi_3'$)
- $\Phi_6'$ is $(-1/(z+1))^2 \cdot e^{z}$

To prove these are holomorphic on the upper half-plane, we need to show they are complex differentiable at each point in $\mathbb{H}$.

